Global industrial data depicts the utilization of more than 10,000 different colours and dyes (Iqbal and Ashiq, 2007), with an estimated dye loss of 1–15 % during the dying process (Senthilkumaar et al., 2005). Even in very low quantities, dyes in water are clearly evident and unappealing. Coloured wastewater containing dyes when released into environmental water bodies are highly toxic effluents and long-term exposure to these dyes in aquatic environments can intermittently lead to environmental contamination and the subsequent endangerment of the food chain, posing risks to human health too. Thus, it is imperative to adequately treat wastewater to remove colours before its release into water sources (
                     Chen et al., 2019
                     ).
